<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-303-532  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 303 532.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  May 1989 v23 n12 p58(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Inoculating against computer viruses.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Steinbrecher, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses have become a major threat to data security, dueto the growing use of PC networks.andP;  A virus is a program which'hides' within another program and replicates itself each time thehost program is run, spreading to any other computers which haveused the original program.andP;  Viruses can destroy data, reformathard disks, or rearrange numerical values.andP;  The primary channelsthrough which viruses spread are internal sabotage and 'free'software downloaded from electronic bulletin boards.andP;  Expertssuggest making regular backup copies of programs and limiting thesharing of files as measures to prevent virus attacks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data SecurityComputer CrimesComputer VirusesSoftwareMicrocomputersSabotage.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>